snippet.textDisplay:
The film is an amazing roller coaster of a cinema ride. It reminded me very much in tone and feel of 'A New Hope'. I liked the fact that they blew through a rediculous amount of ships, planets and characters. The new characters have a lot of snappy dialogue and moments together. It's a great cinema adventure and a lot of fun.

There are a lot of problems though. The Last Jedi tried to be brave and take the series in a brand new direction, which I feel it sorely needed after the wholesale reusing of plot points from the past films. Of course, all the basement dwelling neck beard fans took to Twitter and YouTube and raised a stink. Unfortunately, people at Disney listened to them, even though it should be obvious that the last people you allow near a story are the die-hard fans with no perspective. A fair chunk of 'Rise of Skywalker' deals with retconning all that went before and restoring royal lineage to the Force. Also, again, name and set dropping as many items of the original trilogy as you can. Sigh.

Rian Johnson democratised the Force. In the films, it is stated that the Force is in us ALL, not just royal peeps. Following that ideal would have delivered a much more challenging, and probably satisfying film. Instead, JJ and Disney reinstalled the royal dynamic. Only certain people can use the force now.

Say what you like about the faults of the prequels (and they are legion). At least George tried to do something new and different, whether it worked or not. This trilogy, although more successful on many fronts, has too much of a feel of kids taking all the toys out of the toybox and rearranging them into a new pattern, rather than adults making a new set of toys to play with.

Rise of Skywalker has the unenviable position of ending a trilogy that should never have been started, was unfaithfully executed, and wasted its first film and much of its second. I didn't see it. I made the mistake of seeing The Last Jedi on the strength of Rogue One, which had given me false hope after the disaster that was The Force Awakens.


This entire trilogy is very much like Jurassic Park 3, the opening to which establishes Dr Grant and Dr Sattler as having separated, in order to justify Grant's position in the film. They undid what all the fans considered to be a closed and victorious storyline in order to justify the existence of the film, and then struggled to write a convincing story that wasn't just fan-service sequences. This trilogy does the same, in that it undoes Lucas's closed and victorious storyline of the Original and Prequel trilogies and essentially says "what if: no", spinning off a uninspired and lacklustre trilogy that didn't know what to do with itself. The Force Awakens was an almost exact replica of A New Hope; they just killed off the wisened mentor in the third act instead of the second. I left that film thinking "there are now seven Star Wars films and in THREE of them they blow up the Death Star". They tried so hard to fit absolutely ever aspect of A New Hope into The Force Awakens that they carved up the psyches of their own characters to do it. The rough, whooping boyishness of Han Solo was inserted into Finn's character, which meant that no sooner had he deserted the First Order, having seen his friends die in battle, he was whooping and hollering with glee while blowing them up. What a mess.


The entire point of the original trilogy is the story of Luke Skywalker. The entire point of the original six (i.e. prequels + originals) is the story of two Skywalkers who walk opposite paths and who meet up at the same point to bring balance to the Force. There's a fantastic essay out there called the Star Wars Ring Theory, which explains how the story of all six films is constructed in this brilliant circular structure and is supported by cinematographic choices between each pair of counterpart films. It couldn't be a more closed loop unless Lucas came out and said it in black and white. Undoing that loop to tell a story you haven't even figured out is the height of hubris and nothing short of mercenary.


There is one interesting point that you could use to branch the original six films into a new series, and that's the prophecy of "bringing balance to the Force". If you told a story about how the Jedi's interpretation of "balance" being "all Jedi, no Sith" was foolish, that would be a go-er. But undoing a victory to go an meander off into the nonsense this trilogy did is nothing better than fanfiction.

Because of the crimes and misdemeanour committed by Johnson. And it's sad. So very sad. No reason to talk about the plot? Would you have said the same about the OT? The prosecution rests.

snippet.textDisplay:
The Last Jedi was a terrible film with its numerous contrivances awkward comedy and meandering plot. Rain Johnson attempted to be clever by hitching his story to a philosophy of subverting expectations. In catering to that philosophy of subversion at every point, he manufactured a clunky, inorganic story.
What makes me upset is how film critics that I respect seemed to overlook all the clunky elements they would normally point out about other films and give this film high marks just for being different. Post modern storytelling can be refreshing if executed well. But TLJ failed in the execution.
